r\": \"Exercise can physically increase the size of the hippocampus. This growth is associated with improved memory function and enhanced cognitive abilities.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is neurogenesis, and how does exercise relate to it?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Neurogenesis is the process of generating new brain cells. Exercise promotes neurogenesis, especially in the hippocampus, thereby supporting brain growth and plasticity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is BDNF, and how does it relate to exercise and brain health?\",\n      \"answer\": \"BDNF stands for Brain-Derived Neurotrophic Factor, which is a growth factor. Exercise increases levels of BDNF, which supports the survival of existing neurons and encourages the growth of new neurons and synapses.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"How does exercise protect the brain against neurodegenerative diseases?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Exercise protects the brain by reducing the risk of developing neurodegenerative diseases like Alzheimer's. It helps build a stronger, more resilient brain that is better equipped to resist damage and decline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What is meant by 'brain reserve' in the context of exercise?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Brain reserve refers to the idea that exercise builds a larger and more robust brain. This increased brain volume and resilience allow the brain to better withstand age-related cognitive decline and pathology.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"Can exercise help prevent Alzheimer's disease?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Yes, consistent exercise is shown to significantly reduce the risk and can even delay the onset of neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's disease. It's a powerful preventative measure.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"question\": \"What type of exercise is recommended for optimal brain benefits?\",\n      \"answer\": \"Aerobic exercise is recommended for optimal brain benefits. This includes activities that